05257nam a22007815i 9789814818063DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898148180637 a10.1355/97898148180632doi  a(DE-B1597)522105  a(OCoLC)1100443898  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aBUS0220002bisacsh04a341.76772231 aFlecker, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLegislation on Underwater Cultural Heritage in Southeast Asia :bEvolution and Outcomes /cMichael Flecker. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (35 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tRowing Against the Tide? Batam’s Economic Fortunes in Today’s Indonesia. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tRowing Against the Tide? Batam’s Economic Fortunes in Today’s Indonesia. INTRODUCTION -- tBATAM AND BIDA -- tBATAM’S CURRENT ECONOMIC PERFORMANCE -- tTHE REASONS -- tTHE REASSERTION OF CENTRAL CONTROL -- tOPTIONS FOR THE FUTURE -- tBATAM’S PLACE IN INDONESIA’S ECONOMY -- tCONCLUSION0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis paper examines the evolution of underwater cultural heritage (UCH) legislation in Southeast Asia. Legislation in every country differs, with some reflecting great cultural awareness and some signalling neglect. It seems that some countries regard shipwrecks and their cargoes as resources rather than cultural heritage. Thailand is the only country in Southeast Asia that sponsors its own maritime archaeological programme. Others rely on private funding, usually in exchange for a share of the recovered cargo. These public-private partnerships have in some cases created a culture of corruption, xenophobia, paranoia and greed. Cambodia is the only Southeast Asian signatory to the UNESCO Convention on the Protection of UCH. Other countries follow the UNESCO code of practice, with the exception of key provisions, such as leaving wrecks in situ for future generations, and keeping collections intact. This is not necessarily a bad thing. Indonesia's extreme course of inaction, a moratorium on the issuing of excavation licences, may have exacerbated looting. Fishermen who accidentally find a wreck no longer have a legal means of benefitting from their discovery. They cannot afford to leave valuable ceramics on the seabed for others to loot. Singapore does not have legislation dealing specifically with UCH, although both terrestrial and underwater cultural heritage policy is currently under review. Singapore can afford institutional investigation and excavation, thereby avoiding the pitfalls of private partnerships. Singapore can afford enforcement. By cherry-picking the most effective UCH policies from like-minded governments and moulding them to fit Singapore's unique circumstance Singapore could go from non-starter to leader through a single act of parliament.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCultural property—Protection—Law and legislation—Southeast Asia. 0aShipwrecks—Law and legislation—Southeast Asia. 0aUnderwater archaeology—Law and legislation—Southeast Asia. 4aEconomic Conditions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic Conditions.2bisacsh1 aHutchinson, Francis E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066298608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981481806340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814818063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814818063.jp